<section class="container section-pad" aria-labelledby="quick-answer">
  <h2 id="quick-answer">Quick Answer</h2>
  <p><strong>Do I need a panel upgrade for an EV charger?</strong></p>
  <p>
    Not always. A licensed electrician should verify your panel capacity, service size, load calculation, breaker space,
    charger amperage, and routing path. If capacity exists, a dedicated EV circuit may be enough. If the service is near
    capacity, a panel upgrade, service upgrade, or load management approach may be required.
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Option</th><th>Best For</th><th>Pros</th><th>Watchouts</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr
        ><td>Hardwired EV charger</td><td>Long-term home charging</td><td>Clean look, fewer receptacle issues</td><td
          >Less portable</td
        ></tr
      >
      <tr
        ><td>Plug-in EV charger</td><td>Renters or movable setups</td><td>Can be moved later</td><td
          >Requires correct receptacle and protection strategy</td
        ></tr
      >
      <tr
        ><td>Load management</td><td>Limited panel capacity</td><td>Can avoid unnecessary service upgrades</td><td
          >Requires compatible equipment</td
        ></tr
      >
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <h3>Field Reality: What Homeowners Usually Miss</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>EV charging is a continuous load.</li>
    <li>Breaker space is not the same as electrical capacity.</li>
    <li>Long wire runs can materially change cost.</li>
    <li>Finished garages require more careful routing and patching.</li>
  </ul>
</section>
